Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #medium saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until golden, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Add the @sugar{1/2%tsp} for the onions and cook until caramelised, ~{1-2%minutes} more.

Halve any large @cauliflower florets{300%g} and pop them onto a large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then sprinkle over half the @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden brown and tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once the onion has caramelised, add the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and remaining North Indian style spice mix to the pan. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Meanwhile, drain the @king prawns{150%g}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, lentils and @water{100%ml} for the dal, then bring to a simmer.

Cook until thickened and the lentils are tender, ~{8-10%minutes}. Add a splash of water if it's too thick. When the lentils have 6 mins left, stir in the prawns and cook for the remaining time.

When the cauliflower has 5 mins remaining, remove the tray from the oven. Drizzle over the @honey{1%tbsp}, toss to coat, then roast for the remaining time.

Meanwhile, halve the @lime{1/2}.

Once thickened, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the dal a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from the heat and squeeze in some lime juice. Taste and add salt, pepper and more lime juice if needed.

Spoon the dal into your #serving bowls{} and top with the roasted cauliflower.

Enjoy!

> This North Indian Style King Prawn, Cauliflower and Lentil Dal is bursting full of flavours and makes the perfect dinner night option.

